Analog Channel Release ============================================================ Instruction Overview: ----- Most process related control strategies require input and output of analog field signals. The Analog Channel instruction provides the minimum required functionality for abstracting these analog signals into a usable format. This allows the user to develop a control strategy without requiring knowledge of where the physical signals are sourced, making the logic I/O agnostic. Four primary functionalities are provided: 1. Scaling a raw analog Inp_Data value to engineering units Out_Data. 2. Range-of-control threshold limits with dead band for status indication. 3. Value quality indication (Sts_Fault, Sts_Uncertain). 4. EU value substitution.
Secondary functionality: The Out_Data, Sts_Fault, Val_EUMin, and Val_EUMax output parameters are grouped and arranged to match their corresponding input pin positions on the native Enhanced PID (PIDE) instruction.
Instruction Execution: ----- Continuous
Supplemental Descriptions: ----- The basic functionality of the raM_Dvc_AnalogChannel (Analog Channel) instruction is described below: Signal Scaling – Scale the primary input value to a correlating output value using a simple two -point linear relationship. A configuration flag determines whether the AOI is used to scale a raw input value to engineering units or vice versa. By default, the AOI suitable for scaling a raw analog signal value at the input to engineering units at the output as would be done for an analog input point.
Signal Quality – Comprised of several facets, the signal quality indicator is an accumulation of all conditions that can have a negative effect on the signal value’s fidelity. Components of the quality indicator include input module health, communication link status, input channel health and status, field wiring status, instruction configuration error status, and so forth.
EU Range Limits – Configurable range limits set status flags to indicate when the EU is outside these values. A configurable dead band value prevents excessive status toggling. The instruction can be configured to clamp the EU value between these threshold values.
EU Substitution – Under certain conditions the EU value can be manually set, separating the EU value from the I/O signal. The Substitution value entry is subject to the same threshold limiting as the normal EU value.
Virtual – A status indicator is provided to show when the I/O connection and data is to, or from, a source other than the module.
